# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emacs-editor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The GNU Emacs Manual calls Emacs *the extensible, customizable, self-documenting real-time display editor*, but this description tells beginners little about what Emacs is capable of.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] …as well as tools for compiling, running, and testing programs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You might see now why some people consider Emacs to be not merely a text editor but almost a complete operating system.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some users find that they can do almost all of their work from within Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] This uniformity means that working within Emacs is often easier than learning to use a separate program, especially when that program is liable to have its own set of editing capabilities and shortcuts.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If Emacs doesn't work the way you'd like, you can use the Emacs Lisp (Elisp) language to customize Emacs, automate common tasks, or add new features.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Elisp is very easy to get started with and yet remarkably powerful: you can use it to alter and extend almost any feature of Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can make Emacs whatever you want it to be by writing Elisp code; one testament to this is the fact that all of the features pictured above (and many more described later in this tour) are written in Elisp.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can use the same editor (with the same configuration) on many platforms, including GNU/Linux, BSD and other Unix derivatives, and some proprietary operating systems such as Microsoft Windows.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you install Emacs first, you can follow along with the examples presented here.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Whenever you decide to start using Emacs, you should take the Emacs tutorial.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] To run the tutorial, start Emacs and type C-h t, that is, Ctrl-h followed by t.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] All the features described in this tour work in GNU Emacs 23.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some features described weren't included in previous versions of Emacs but can be installed separately.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] This refers to a page in the Emacs manual which you can read by following the link.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] However, you can also read such pages directly in Emacs by using the built-in documentation reader, called Info.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The Emacs manual is an excellent resource for learning about Emacs; you can read it from within Emacs by typing C-h r.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can also read the manual on the web.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs has numerous other help features, some of which will be described later.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can view a list of all help features by typing C-h C-h.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs gives you a large collection of tools for manipulating text, which turns out to be a Swiss army knife of sorts because Emacs also has ways to present all kinds of information in text.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] M-x dired invokes *Dired*, the file manager mode, on a directory of your choice.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] In this mode, changing the filenames in the right-hand job and then typing C-x C-s ("save") renames the indicated files.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Renaming files is as easy as editing text.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Batch renaming (e.g., renaming every file of the form `icon_*` to `backup_icon_*`) is as easy as performing a search and replace (M-x query-replace or M-%); there's no need to learn to use a separate batch renaming tool.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Because of this integration, the benefits of learning to use any of Emacs' editing features (say, search and replace) are multiplied many times over.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] One way that Emacs lets users work quickly and efficiently is by providing high-level commands for moving around in, and manipulating, text.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] There are commands that operate on characters, words, lines, sentences, paragraphs, pages, function definitions, whitespace, and more.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can use them anywhere you read or edit text: source code, web pages, shells, directory listings, email messages, and so on.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] When you get used to these keys, they're faster than their more familiar equivalents in other applications (Home, End, Ctrl+Left, etc.) because you don't have to move your hands from the touch typing position.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] And these keys are far faster than using a mouse to move around in a buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs often provides additional commands for moving around in context-specific ways (e.g. in source code, commands to move to the previous or next function definition).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Many of the above commands move to a location relative to your current position in the buffer, so you can use them repeatedly (e.g.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can use the *prefix argument* to save time: C-u followed by a number and a movement command repeats that command the specified number of times.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can also use M-[digit] instead of C-u [digit].
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you use C-u without specifying a digit, the default is 4.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Omitting the digit can save time when you don't know precisely how many units you want to jump anyway.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Searching for text is a handy way to move around in a buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Think of search as just another facility for movement.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] When you're looking for something specific, you can use incremental search to take you right there instead of scanning by lines or pages.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs remembers something called the *mark*, which is a previous cursor position.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can set mark to indicate a particular place in your buffer so you can return to it easily.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] C-x C-x at a later time will return point to mark.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Actually, that command also moves mark to where point formerly was; therefore, a second C-x C-x returns point to its original position.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] As you can see, Emacs tries to be helpful: many commands that have the potential to take you long distances set mark so that a simple C-x C-x takes you back to where you were.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] *Emacs makes it difficult to lose your place in a buffer*: even if you take a detour, you don't need to scroll around to get back to where you were.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs saves many previous values of the mark for you.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Mark serves another purpose: mark and point together delineate *the region*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Many commands operate only on the text in the region (i.e. between mark and point).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can set the region explicitly by setting mark (C-SPC) and then moving point elsewhere, or by clicking and dragging with the mouse.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Other commands helpfully set the region as part of what they do.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] C-y (yank), inserting a file, and inserting a buffer all set the region to surround the inserted text.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] For more information see (info "(emacs)Narrowing").
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] As with text movement, Emacs provides commands for deleting text in various amounts.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] C-k kills the portion of the current line after point (or deletes the newline following point if point is at the end of line).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] All of the above commands *kill* the text being deleted, which means that Emacs removes the text and squirrels it away for later retrieval ("yanking").
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Most commands which delete significant amounts of text kill it rather than simply removing it, so that you can use those commands either to "delete" text or to "cut" it for later use.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] After a piece of text has been killed, it goes to a place called the *kill ring* which is analagous to the "clipboard": you can *yank* an item to restore it from the kill ring with C-y.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Unlike the clipboard, however, the kill ring is capable of holding many different items.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If the item you want to yank is not placed when you type C-y, type M-y (repeatedly, if necessary) to cycle through previously killed items.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Recall that most commands which delete a large amount of text in fact kill it (i.e. place it in the kill ring) so you can restore it later.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] *Emacs makes it very difficult to lose a lot of text permanently*: in editors with only a single clipboard, one can easily accidentally delete a large chunk of text or clobber the contents of the clipboard (by cutting two items in succession).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] But in Emacs, in either of those cases, the lost text can easily be retrieved from the kill ring.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs' undo facility works slightly differently from that of other editors.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] In most editors, if you undo some changes, then make some new changes, the states formerly accessible with "redo" can no longer be recovered!
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] So when using "undo" and "redo" extensively, one has to be very careful to avoid accidentally clobbering the redo list.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs uses a different undo model which does not have this deficiency.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] After any consecutive sequence of undos, Emacs makes all your previous actions undoable, including the undos.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If this sounds complicated, just remember that "undo" is always capable of getting you back to *any previous state your buffer was in* (unless Emacs has run out of memory to store the undo history).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The principle here is that *Emacs makes it very difficult to accidentally lose your work*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] So if you need to get back to a previous buffer state, simply move the cursor (so as to break any existing sequence of undos), and press C-/ until you find what you want.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] To learn more about undo, see (info "(emacs)Undo").
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Typing C-s followed by some text starts incremental search.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs jumps to the next occurrence of whatever you have typed, as you are typing it (you may have seen similar behavior in Mozilla Firefox or other web browsers), and all matches visible on your screen are highlighted.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Within incremental search, you can type C-s again at any time to jump to the next occurrence.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] When you've found what you're looking for, you can either type RET (or use almost any movement command) to exit search at the occurrence you've found, or C-g ("cancel") to return to where your search started.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you exit search at the found occurrence, you can easily jump back to where you started with C-x C-x since incremental search sets mark appropriately.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can perform a backward incremental search with C-r.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] (All the above commands can be activated similarly from within backward search.) At any time during a forward (or backward) search, you can type C-r (C-s) to switch to a backward (forward) search.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Incremental Search") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The query replace command prompts you for a search string and a replacement.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Then, for each match in the buffer, you can choose whether or not to replace the search string.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Query Replace") for more information about these (and other) options.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can also type ? anytime inside a search-and-replace operation to see a guide.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Regular expressions are a succinct way of searching for many different strings at once by using a special language to describe the form of what you're looking for.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Regular expression syntax is beyond the scope of this tour; see (info "(emacs)Regexps") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you're new to regexps, or you are constructing a particularly complicated regexp, you can use the regexp builder (M-x re-builder).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] This command pops up a separate window in which you can test out your regexp, and any matches in your original buffer will get highlighted as you edit your regexp.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Instead of jumping through matches one by one, you can also choose to display them all at once.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] M-x occur prompts you for a regular expression, then displays in a separate buffer a list of all lines in the current buffer which match that regexp (as well as their line numbers).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Clicking on any occurrence takes you to that line in the buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Regular expressions are even more powerful in search and replace, because Emacs allows the replacement text to depend on the found text.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] As you can see, regexp replacement is capable of doing some pretty sophisticated transformations.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Keyboard macros are a way to remember a fixed sequence of keys for later repetition.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] They're handy for automating some boring editing tasks.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] After we record that key sequence as a macro, we can type M-0 F4 to transform the buffer pictured earlier; in this case, Emacs runs the macro repeatedly until it has reached the end of the buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Keyboard Macros") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you've read this far, you are probably intimidated by the thought of having to remember a bunch of keyboard commands and command names.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Fortunately, Emacs includes comprehensive and easily accessible documentation.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The documentation isn't just for beginners.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs has thousands of commands, of which most people only use a small number.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] So even Emacs experts frequently consult the docs in order to learn about new commands or jog their memory on old ones.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Shows documentation for the command associated with any particular key.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] This is handy, for example, if you don't remember what C-s does, or if you remember that it invokes incremental search but want to know more about that feature.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The documentation gives the full name of the command, shows which (if any) keys are bound to it, and gives a complete description of what the command does.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] For example, if I remember that I want to activate *narrowing*, but don't remember how, I can type C-h a narrow RET which shows a brief list of commands having to do with *narrow*, one of which is M-x narrow-to-region.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs is notable for its integration with many common tools.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Not only can you invoke them from within the editor, Emacs usually helps you use their output more effectively.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Starts a shell in the buffer named `*shell*`, switching to it if it already exists.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Use C-u M-x shell to use a buffer with a different name.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Invokes `make` (with targets and options of your choice) and displays output in a new buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs identifies error lines containing filenames and line numbers, and you can click on them to jump directly to the corresponding buffer and line.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can use the gdb command line as usual in that buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] However, Emacs lets you set breakpoints directly from your source buffers and shows execution by marking the active line in your source buffers.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs can also display breakpoints, the stack, and locals, simultaneously and each in their own window.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Invokes `grep` and prints results in a new buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Like M-x compile, when you click on a match Emacs opens the correct file and takes you to the matching line.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Executes a command and displays the output in a new buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Executes a command, piping in the current region as input; displays the output in a new buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] For either command, a C-u prefix will insert the output in your current buffer rather than using a temporary buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs helps you manipulate and edit files stored in version control.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs supports CVS, Subversion, bzr, git, hg, and other systems, but it offers a uniform interface, called VC, regardless of the version control system you are using.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs automatically detects when a file you're editing is under version control, and displays something like this in the mode line: CVS-1.14 to indicate the version control system in use, and the current version.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] M-x vc-next-action or C-x v v commits the current file (prompting you for a log message) if you've modified it.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Displays a diff showing the changes you've made to the current file.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Prompts you for a version number and shows you that version of the current file in another window.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Displays an annotated version of the file showing, for each line, the commit where that line was last changed and by whom.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] On any line you can press L to view the log message for that commit or D to view the associated diff.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Displays a log of previous changes to the file.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] When the cursor is on a particular log entry, you can press d to view the diff associated with that change or f to view that version of the file.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Version Control") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some special features are enabled when you are looking at a diff (whether from a file, or one produced by VC).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs lets you move around in a diff by hunks or files, apply individual hunks to a file, reverse a diff, and do other operations useful for reading or manually editing diffs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Diff Mode") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs can edit remote files transparently (as if they were local) using a feature called Tramp.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Whenever Emacs asks for a file, you can indicate a remote file like so: /myname@remotehost:/remote/path/to/file.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs retrieves the file over SSH, FTP, or another method and takes care of saving it when you're done.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] With Tramp you can edit files on different computers using a single Emacs session, even if Emacs is not installed on the remote side.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can also use Tramp to edit local files with another user's permissions.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can edit files with root privileges via sudo: /sudo::/etc/file, or via su: /root@localhost:/etc/file.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(TRAMP)") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some people like to keep only a single instance of Emacs open and edit all their files in there.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Alas, when you type emacs in a shell to edit a file (or when `$EDITOR` is invoked by an external program), a new instance of Emacs is started.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] To edit a file, type emacsclient -t FILENAME at a prompt.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can also change your `$EDITOR` to `emacsclient -t` if you're using programs that automatically invoke `$EDITOR`.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] When you're done editing, type C-x C-c, which closes the frame.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] For more information, see (info "(emacs)Emacs Server").
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you ever get confused, the documentation for any command (accessible with C-h f or C-h k) describes the effect of the prefix argument, if any.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Arguments") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Every buffer has an associated *major mode*, which alters certain behaviors, key bindings, and text display in that buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The idea is to customize the appearance and features available based on the contents of the buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs ships with dozens of major modes for editing widely used programming languages, markup languages, and configuration file formats.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some commands we've seen, like M-x dired, M-x compile, and M-x shell, in fact use their own special major modes to make their buffers provide certain features (such as highlighting compile errors and making them clickable).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The current major mode is displayed in the mode line.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The last thing on the mode line should be one or more items in parentheses, like `(Python Narrow)`.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The first of these is the name of the major mode.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs is very good at determining the right mode to use when you open a file, so you'll rarely have to use the above commands.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] In almost all cases, major modes for unsupported formats are available as extension packages.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Major Modes") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Every buffer can also have any number of *minor modes*, which are extra pieces of functionality you can enable, independently of each other and of the major mode.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Minor modes are listed in the mode line after the major mode inside the parentheses.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Wraps your lines automatically when they get longer than 70 characters.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Highlights misspelled words as you type.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some minor modes are global, i.e. they affect the behavior of the entire editor, rather than just that of a specific buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] In the M-x prompt (and elsewhere), show completions as you type.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Show all buffer names when you switch buffers with C-x b.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] See (info "(emacs)Minor Modes") for more information.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If you need help with a particular mode, C-h m describes the active major and minor modes.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The mode description often lists important commands which are useful in that mode, which is helpful when you're learning to use a new mode.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The minibuffer (the space at the bottom of the frame) is where Emacs prompts you for input in most situations: for a command, when you type M-x; for a file name, within M-x find-file; for an Elisp expression, within M-x eval-expression, etc.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] C-g also cancels a long-running operation if it appears that Emacs has frozen.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some Emacs users remap their Caps Lock key to act as an additional Ctrl key, because it is easier to reach.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If your DEL key is not working (sometimes, typing DEL brings up a help screen, as if you typed C-h), try M-x normal-erase-is-backspace-mode.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] If your meta key is not working, in order to type a key that contains meta, you can instead type ESC, then the remaining keys.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] For example, ESC x is the same as M-x, and ESC C-s is the same as C-M-s.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs comes with a FAQ which explains how to perform many commonly requested tasks; press C-h C-f to read it.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Emacs has a number of options for easing the transition from other editing environments.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] In Windows, the bread and butter editing commands are C-z, C-x, C-c, and C-v.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Unfortunately, these keys are frequently used in Emacs for other purposes (suspend, prefix key, prefix key, and next page).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can get those keys back for Undo, Cut, Copy, and Paste by turning on "CUA mode" from the Options menu.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] CUA mode also lets you make a selection by using Shift in combination with movement keys, as you would do on Windows.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Since C-x and C-c are so integral to Emacs operation (they are prefix keys for many commands), CUA mode only binds C-x and C-c to Cut and Copy, respectively, when you have selected some text.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can learn more about CUA mode by typing C-h f cua-mode RET.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Viper (M-x viper-mode) is a set of modes for emulating vi editing behavior in Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] It provides different levels of vi-adherence, depending on how vi-like you want your Emacs to be.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] For more information about Viper, see (info "(viper)").
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The GNU Emacs Manual (C-h r) is the definitive guide if you want to learn more about Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] Some Emacs features have their own, separate manuals (C-h i d).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] The GNU Emacs FAQ (C-h C-f) answers many questions that beginners have about how Emacs works and how to set it up to do particular things.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] EmacsWiki contains information about many downloadable Emacs extensions, as well as tips for using and customizing Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs-tour] You can ask questions on the help-gnu-emacs mailing list.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Emacs has over 10,000 built-in commands and its user interface allows the user to combine these commands into macros to automate work.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Implementations of Emacs typically feature a dialect of the Lisp programming language, allowing users and developers to write new commands and applications for the editor.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Extensions have been written to, among other things, manage files, remote access, e-mail, outlines, multimedia, Git integration, RSS feeds, and collaborative editing, as well as implementations of *ELIZA*, *Pong*, *Conway's Life*, *Snake*, *Dunnet*, and *Tetris*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The original EMACS was written in 1976 by David A.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Steele Jr. as a set of macros for the TECO editor.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] It was inspired by the ideas of the TECO-macro editors TECMAC and TMACS.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The most popular, and most ported, version of Emacs is GNU Emacs, which was created by Richard Stallman for the GNU Project.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] XEmacs is a variant that branched from GNU Emacs in 1991.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs and XEmacs use similar Lisp dialects and are, for the most part, compatible with each other.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] XEmacs development is currently very slow.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs is, along with vi, one of the two main contenders in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs is among the oldest free and open source projects still under development.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Emacs development began during the 1970s at the MIT AI Lab, whose PDP-6 and PDP-10 computers used the Incompatible Timesharing System (ITS) operating system that featured a default line editor known as Text Editor and Corrector (TECO).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Unlike most modern text editors, TECO used separate modes in which the user would either add text, edit existing text, or display the document.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] (A similar technique was used to allow overtyping.) This behavior is similar to that of the program ed.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] By the 1970s, TECO was already an old program, initially released in 1962.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Richard Stallman visited the Stanford AI Lab in 1976 and saw the lab's *E* editor, written by Fred Wright.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] He was impressed by the editor's intuitive WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get) behavior, which has since become the default behavior of most modern text editors.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] He returned to MIT where Carl Mikkelsen, a hacker at the AI Lab, had added to TECO a combined display/editing mode called *Control-R* that allowed the screen display to be updated each time the user entered a keystroke.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Stallman reimplemented this mode to run efficiently and then added a macro feature to the TECO display-editing mode that allowed the user to redefine any keystroke to run a TECO program.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] E had another feature that TECO lacked: random-access editing.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] TECO was a page-sequential editor that was designed for editing paper tape on the PDP-1 at a time when computer memory was generally small due to cost, and it was a feature of TECO that allowed editing on only one page at a time sequentially in the order of the pages in the file.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Instead of adopting E's approach of structuring the file for page-random access on disk, Stallman modified TECO to handle large buffers more efficiently and changed its file-management method to read, edit, and write the entire file as a single buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Almost all modern editors use this approach.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The new version of TECO quickly became popular at the AI Lab and soon accumulated a large collection of custom macros whose names often ended in *MAC* or *MACS*, which stood for *macro*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Two years later, Guy Steele took on the project of unifying the diverse macros into a single set.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Steele and Stallman's finished implementation included facilities for extending and documenting the new macro set.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The resulting system was called EMACS, which stood for *Editing MACroS* or, alternatively, *E with MACroS*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Later, the use of EMACS as a recursive acronym for *EMACS Makes All Computing Simple* became popular; this fit in with the growing use of recursive acronyms for other versions of EMACS.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] (See below.) Stallman picked the name Emacs "because <E> was not in use as an abbreviation on ITS at the time." An apocryphal hacker koan alleges that the program was named after Emack & Bolio's, a popular Boston ice cream store.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The first operational EMACS system existed in late 1976.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Stallman saw a problem in too much customization and *de facto* forking and set certain conditions for usage.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The original Emacs ran only on the PDP-10 running ITS.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Its behavior was sufficiently different from that of TECO that it could be considered a text editor in its own right, and it quickly became the standard editing program on ITS.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Mike McMahon ported Emacs from ITS to the TENEX and TOPS-20 operating systems.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Other contributors to early versions of Emacs include Kent Pitman, Earl Killian, and Eugene Ciccarelli.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] By 1979, Emacs was the main editor used in MIT's AI lab and its Laboratory for Computer Science.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In the following years, programmers wrote a variety of Emacs-like editors for other computer systems.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] These included EINE (*EINE Is Not EMACS*) and ZWEI (*ZWEI Was EINE Initially*), which were written for the Lisp machine by Mike McMahon and Daniel Weinreb, and Sine (*Sine Is Not Eine*), which was written by Owen Theodore Anderson.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Weinreb's EINE was the first Emacs written in Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In 1978, Bernard Greenberg wrote Multics Emacs almost entirely in Multics Lisp at Honeywell's Cambridge Information Systems Lab.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Multics Emacs was later maintained by Richard Soley, who went on to develop the NILE Emacs-like editor for the NIL Project, and by Barry Margolin.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Many versions of Emacs, including GNU Emacs, would later adopt Lisp as an extension language.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] James Gosling, who would later invent NeWS and the Java programming language, wrote Gosling Emacs in 1981.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The first Emacs-like editor to run on Unix, Gosling Emacs was written in C and used Mocklisp, a language with Lisp-like syntax, as an extension language.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Early ads for Computer Corporation of America's *CCA EMACS* (Steve Zimmerman) appeared in 1984.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] CCA EMACS was originally based on Warren Montgomery's EMACS, but was gradually rewritten so that by the time of its commercial release in 1983, none of Montgomery's code was present anymore.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] CCA EMACS was written to emulate the original PDP-10 EMACS (written by Richard Stallman) as closely as possible, while adding many new commands as well.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In 1984, in a competition with other versions of Emacs, it won a site license from MIT for their Project Athena.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Richard Stallman began work on GNU Emacs in 1984 to produce a free software alternative to the proprietary Gosling Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs was initially based on Gosling Emacs, but Stallman's replacement of its Mocklisp interpreter with a true Lisp interpreter required that nearly all of its code be rewritten.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This became the first program released by the nascent GNU Project.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs is written in C and provides Emacs Lisp, also implemented in C, as an extension language.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Version 13, the first public release, was made on March 20, 1985.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The first widely distributed version of GNU Emacs was version 15.34, released later in 1985.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Early versions of GNU Emacs were numbered as *1.x.x*, with the initial digit denoting the version of the C core.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The *1* was dropped after version 1.12, as it was thought that the major number would never change, and thus the numbering skipped from *1* to *13*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In September 2014, it was announced on the GNU emacs-devel mailing list that GNU Emacs would adopt a rapid release strategy and version numbers would increment more quickly in the future.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs offered more features than Gosling Emacs, in particular a full-featured Lisp as its extension language, and soon replaced Gosling Emacs as the *de facto* Unix Emacs editor.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Markus Hess exploited a security flaw in GNU Emacs' email subsystem in his 1986 cracking spree in which he gained superuser access to Unix computers.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Most of GNU Emacs functionality is implemented through a scripting language called Emacs Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Because about 70% of GNU Emacs is written in the Emacs Lisp extension language, one only needs to port the C core which implements the Emacs Lisp interpreter.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This makes porting Emacs to a new platform considerably less difficult than porting an equivalent project consisting of native code only.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs development was relatively closed until 1999 and was used as an example of the *Cathedral* development style in *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The project has since adopted a public development mailing list and anonymous CVS access.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Development took place in a single CVS trunk until 2008 and was then switched to the Bazaar DVCS.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] On November 11, 2014, development was moved to Git.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Richard Stallman has remained the principal maintainer of GNU Emacs, but he has stepped back from the role at times.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Stefan Monnier and Chong Yidong were maintainers from 2008 to 2015.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] John Wiegley was named maintainer in 2015 after a meeting with Stallman at MIT.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Wiegley stepped down in 2018, leaving Eli Zaretskii as lead maintainer.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Stefan Kangas was appointed as co-maintainer in 2023, and Andrea Corallo joined Zaretskii and Kangas in 2024.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] As of 2025, GNU Emacs has had 1,608 individual committers throughout its history.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Lucid Emacs, based on an early alpha version of GNU Emacs 19, was developed beginning in 1991 by Jamie Zawinski and others at Lucid Inc.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] One of the best-known early forks in free software development occurred when the codebases of the two Emacs versions diverged and the separate development teams ceased efforts to merge them back into a single program.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Lucid Emacs has since been renamed XEmacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Its development is currently very slow, with the most recent stable version 21.4.22 released in January 2009, and the most recent beta released in June 2025; meanwhile, GNU Emacs has implemented many formerly XEmacs-only features.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In the past, projects aimed at producing small versions of Emacs proliferated.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs was initially targeted at computers with a 32-bit flat address space and at least 1 MiB of RAM.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Such computers were high end workstations and minicomputers in the 1980s, and this left a need for smaller reimplementations that would run on common personal computer hardware.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Today's computers have more than enough power and capacity to eliminate these restrictions, but small clones have more recently been designed to fit on software installation disks or for use on less capable hardware.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Other projects aim to implement Emacs in a different dialect of Lisp or a different programming language altogether.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Emacs is primarily a text editor and is designed for manipulating pieces of text, although it is capable of formatting and printing documents like a word processor by interfacing with external programs such as LaTeX, Ghostscript or a web browser.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Emacs provides commands to manipulate and differentially display semantic units of text such as words, sentences, paragraphs and source code constructs such as functions.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] It also features *keyboard macros* for performing user-defined batches of editing commands.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] GNU Emacs is a *real-time display* editor, as its edits are displayed onscreen as they occur.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This is standard behavior for modern text editors but EMACS was among the earliest to implement this.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The alternative is having to issue a distinct command to display text, (e.g. before or after modifying it).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This was common in earlier (or merely simpler) line and context editors, such as QED (BTS, CTSS, Multics), ed (Unix), ED (CP/M), and Edlin (DOS).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Almost all of the functionality in Emacs, including basic editing operations such as the insertion of characters into a file, is achieved through functions written in a dialect of the Lisp programming language.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The dialect used in GNU Emacs is known as Emacs Lisp (Elisp), and was developed expressly to port Emacs to GNU and Unix.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In this Lisp environment, variables and functions can be modified with no need to rebuild or restart Emacs, with even newly redefined versions of core editor features being asynchronously compiled and loaded into the live environment to replace existing definitions.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Modern GNU Emacs features both bytecode and native code compilation for Emacs Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] All configuration is stored in variables, classes, and data structures, and changed by simply updating these live.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In this way there is little difference in practice between customising existing features and writing new ones, both of which are accomplished in the same basic way.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This is operatively different from most modern extensible editors, for instance VS Code, in which separate languages are used to implement the interface and features of the editor and to encode its user-defined configuration and options.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The main text editing data structure is the *buffer*, a memory region containing data (usually text) with associated attributes.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Any interaction with the editor (like key presses or clicking a mouse button) is realized by evaluating Emacs Lisp code, typically a *command*, which is a function explicitly designed for interactive use.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Keys can be arbitrarily redefined and commands can also be accessed by name; some commands evaluate arbitrary Emacs Lisp code provided by the user in various ways (e.g. a family of `eval-` functions, operating on the `buffer`, `region`, or individual `expression`).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Even the simplest user inputs (such a printable characters) are effectuated as Emacs Lisp functions, such as the `self-insert-command`, bound by default to most keyboard keys in a typical text editing buffer, mapping the key used to call it into the associated locale-defined character.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] For example, pressing the f key in a buffer that accepts text input evaluates the code `(self-insert-command 1 ?f)`, which inserts one copy of the character constant `?f` *at point*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The `1`, in this case, is determined by what Emacs terms the *universal argument*: all Emacs command code accepts a numeric value which, in its simplest usage, indicates repetition of an action, but in more complex cases (where repetition doesn't make sense) can yield other behaviours.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] These arguments may be supplied via command prefixes, such as Control+u 7 f, or more compactly Meta+7 f, which expands to `(self-insert-command 7 ?f)`.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] When no prefix is supplied, the universal argument is `1`: every command implicitly runs once, but may be called multiply, or in a different way, when supplied with such a prefix.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Such arguments may also be non-positive where it makes sense for them to be so - it is up to the function accepting the argument to determine, according to its own semantics, what a given number means to it.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] One common usage is for functions to perform actions in reverse simply by checking the sign of the universal argument, such as a sort command which sorts in obverse by default and in reverse when called with a negative argument, using the absolute value of its argument as the sorting key (e.g.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] `-7` sorting in reverse by column index (or delimiter) 7), or undo/redo, which are simply negatives of each other (traversing forward and backward through a recursive history of diffs by some number of steps at a time).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Because of its relatively large vocabulary of commands, Emacs features a long-established *command language*, to concisely express the keystrokes necessary to perform an action.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This command language recognises the following shift and modifier keys: Ctrl, Alt, ⇧ Shift, Meta, Super, and Hyper.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Not all of these may be present on an IBM-style keyboard, though they can usually be configured as desired.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] These are represented in command language as the respective prefices: `C-`, `A-`, `S-`, `M-`, `s-`, and `H-`.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Keys whose names are only printable with more than one character are enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Because Emacs predates modern standard terminology for graphical user interfaces, it uses somewhat divergent names for familiar interface elements.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Depending on configuration, windows can include their own scroll bars, line numbers, sometimes a 'header line' typically to ease navigation, and a *mode line* at the bottom (usually displaying buffer name, the active modes and point position of the buffer among others).
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The bottom of every frame is used for output messages (then called 'echo area') and text input for commands (then called 'minibuffer').
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In general, Emacs display elements (windows, frames, etc.) do not belong to any specific data or process.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Just as buffers don't require windows, running Emacs processes do not require any frames, and one common usage pattern is to deploy Emacs as an *editing server*: running it as a headless daemon and connecting to it via a frame-spawning client.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This server can then be made available in any situation where an editor is required, simply by declaring the client program to be the user's `EDITOR` or `VISUAL` variable.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] In this mode of operation, Emacs overlaps the functionality of programs like screen and tmux.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The first Emacs contained a *help* library that included documentation for every command, variable and internal function.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Because of this, Emacs proponents described the software as *self-documenting* in that it presents the user with information on its normal features and its current state.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Each function includes a documentation string that is displayed to the user on request, a practice that subsequently spread to programming languages including Lisp, Java, Perl, and Python.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This help system can take users to the actual code for each function, whether from a built-in library or an added third-party library.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Emacs displays instructions for performing simple editing commands and invoking the tutorial when it is launched with no file to edit.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The tutorial is by Stuart Cracraft and Richard Stallman.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The *Church of Emacs*, formed by Richard Stallman, is a parody religion created for Emacs users.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] While it refers to vi as the *editor of the beast* (vi-vi-vi being 6-6-6 in Roman numerals), it does not oppose the use of vi; rather, it calls it proprietary software anathema.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] ("Using a free version of vi is not a sin but a penance.") The Church of Emacs has its own newsgroup, alt.religion.emacs, that has posts purporting to support this parody religion.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Supporters of vi have created an opposing *Cult of vi*.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Stallman has jokingly referred to himself as *St I GNU cius*, a saint in the Church of Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] This is in reference to Ignatius of Antioch, an early Church father venerated in Christianity.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] There is folklore attributing a repetitive strain injury colloquially called *Emacs pinky* to Emacs' strong dependence on modifier keys, although there have not been any studies done to show Emacs causes more such problems than other keyboard-heavy computer programs.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Users have addressed this through various approaches.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] Some users recommend simply using the two Control keys on typical PC keyboards like Shift keys while touch typing to avoid overly straining the left pinky, a proper use of the keyboard will reduce the RSI.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The *Emacs pinky* is a relatively recent development.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The Space-cadet keyboard on which Emacs was developed had oversized Control keys that were adjacent to the space bar and were easy to reach with the thumb.
[src:emacs-editor/emacs] The word *emacs* is sometimes pluralized as *emacsen*, by phonetic analogy with boxen and VAXen, referring to different varieties of Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The program's tagline is "the extensible self-documenting text editor." Most functionality in GNU Emacs is implemented in user-accessible Emacs Lisp, allowing deep extensibility directly by users and through community-contributed packages.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Its built-in features include a file browser and editor (Dired), an advanced calculator (Calc), an email client and news reader (Gnus), a Language Server Protocol integration, and the productivity system Org-mode.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] A large community of users have contributed extensions such as the Git interface Magit, the Vim emulation layer Evil, several search frameworks, the window manager EXWM, and tools for working with a wide range of programming languages.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Steele Jr. as a set of macros for the TECO editor, and in 1984, Richard Stallman began work on GNU Emacs, to produce a free software replacement to the proprietary Gosling Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] This became the first program released by the then-nascent GNU Project.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Early versions of GNU Emacs were numbered as "1.x.x," with the initial digit denoting the version of the C core.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The "1" was dropped after version 1.12 as it was thought that the major number would never change, and thus the major version skipped from "1" to "13".
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] A new third version number was added to represent changes made by user sites.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In the current numbering scheme, a number with two components signifies a release version, with development versions having three components.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs was later ported to the Unix operating system.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] It offered more features than Gosling Emacs, in particular a full-featured Lisp as its extension language, and soon replaced Gosling Emacs as the *de facto* Unix Emacs editor.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Markus Hess exploited a security flaw in GNU Emacs's email subsystem in his 1986 cracking spree, in which he gained superuser access to Unix computers.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Although users commonly submitted patches and Elisp code to the net.emacs newsgroup, participation in GNU Emacs development was relatively restricted until 1999, and was used as an example of the "Cathedral" development style in *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Development took place in a single CVS trunk until 2008, and today uses the Git DVCS.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Stefan Monnier and Chong Yidong oversaw maintenance from 2008.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] On September 21, 2015, Monnier announced that he would be stepping down as maintainer effective with the feature freeze of Emacs 25.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Longtime contributor John Wiegley was announced as the new maintainer on November 5, 2015.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Wiegley was joined by Eli Zaretskii in July, 2016, and Lars Ingebrigtsen in September, 2020.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Wiegley stepped down in 2018, and Ingebrigtsen concluded his term with the release of Emacs 29.1, leaving Zaretskii as lead maintainer.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The terms of the GNU General Public License (GPL) state that the Emacs source code, including both the C and Emacs Lisp components, are freely available for examination, modification, and redistribution.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Older versions of the GNU Emacs documentation appeared under an ad-hoc license that required the inclusion of certain text in any modified copy.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In the GNU Emacs user's manual, for example, this included instructions for obtaining GNU Emacs and Richard Stallman's essay *The GNU Manifesto*.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The XEmacs manuals, which were inherited from older GNU Emacs manuals when the fork occurred, have the same license.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Newer versions of the documentation use the GNU Free Documentation License with "invariant sections" that require the inclusion of the same documents and that the manuals proclaim themselves as *GNU Manuals*.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] This policy is in place so that the FSF can defend the software in court if its copyleft license is violated.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In 2011, it was noticed that GNU Emacs had been accidentally releasing some binaries without corresponding source code for two years, in opposition to the intended spirit of the GPL.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Richard Stallman described this incident as "a very bad mistake," which was promptly fixed.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The FSF did not sue any downstream redistributors who unknowingly violated the GPL by distributing these binaries.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In its normal editing mode, GNU Emacs behaves like common text editors by allowing the user to type text with the keyboard and move the editing point with arrow keys.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Escape key sequences or pressing the control key and/or the meta key, alt key or super keys in conjunction with a regular key produces modified keystrokes that invoke functions from the Emacs Lisp environment.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Commands such as `save-buffer` and `save-buffers-kill-emacs` combine multiple modified keystrokes.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Some GNU Emacs commands work by invoking external programs, such as ispell for spell-checking and the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) for program compilation.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs also supports "inferior processes," long-lived child processes that interact with the editor.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] This is used to implement shell-mode, running a Unix shell as inferior process, as well as read–eval–print loop (REPL) modes for various programming languages.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs' support for external processes makes it suitable for interactive programming along the lines of Interlisp or Smalltalk.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Users who prefer the widely used IBM Common User Access keyboard shortcut layout can use cua-mode, a package that originally was a third-party add-on but has been included in GNU Emacs since version 22.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs uses the "minibuffer," normally the bottommost line, to display messages and request information, functions that are often performed by dialog boxes in GUI editors.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The minibuffer holds information such as text to target in a search or the name of a file to read or save.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] When applicable, command-line completion is available using the tab and space keys.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs keeps text in data structures known as buffers.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Buffers may or may not be displayed onscreen, and all buffer features are accessible by both Emacs Lisp programs and the user interface.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The user can create new buffers and dismiss unwanted ones, and many buffers can exist at the same time, limited only by available memory.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs can be configured to save the list of open buffers on exit, and reopen this list when it is restarted.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Some buffers contain text loaded from text files, which the user can edit and save back to permanent storage.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] These buffers are said to be "visiting" files.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Buffers also serve to display other data, such as the output of Emacs commands, dired directory listings, documentation strings displayed by the "help" library and notification messages that in other editors would be displayed in a dialog box.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Some of these notifications are displayed briefly in the minibuffer, and GNU Emacs provides a *Messages* buffer that keeps a history of the most recent notifications of this type.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] When the minibuffer is used for output from Emacs, it is called the "echo area".
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Longer notifications are displayed in buffers of their own.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The maximum length of messages that will be displayed in the minibuffer is, of course, configurable.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Buffers can also serve as input and output areas for an external process such as a shell or REPL.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Buffers which Emacs creates on its own are typically named with asterisks on each end, to distinguish from user buffers.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The list of open buffers is itself displayed in this type of buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Most Emacs key sequences remain functional in any buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] For example, the standard Ctrl-s `isearch` function can be used to search filenames in dired buffers, and the file list can be saved to a text file just as any other buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Dired buffers can be switched to a writable mode, in which filenames and attributes can be edited textually; when the buffer is saved, the changes are written to the filesystem.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] This allows multiple files to be renamed using the search and replace features of Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] When so equipped, Emacs displays image files in buffers.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs can split the editing area into separate non-overlapping sections called "windows," a feature that has been available since 1975, predating the graphical user interface in common use.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In Emacs terminology, "windows" are similar to what other systems call "frames" or "panes" – a rectangular portion of the program's display that can be updated and interacted with independently.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Each Emacs window has a status bar called the "mode line" displayed by default at the bottom edge of the window.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs windows are available both in text-terminal and graphical modes and allow more than one buffer, or several parts of a buffer, to be displayed at once.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In addition, there is follow-mode, a minor mode that chains windows to display non-overlapping portions of a buffer.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Using follow-mode, a single file can be displayed in multiple side-by-side windows that update appropriately when scrolled.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In addition, Emacs supports "narrowing" a buffer to display only a portion of a file, with top/bottom of buffer navigation functionality and buffer size calculations reflecting only the selected range.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs windows are tiled and cannot appear "above" or "below" their companions.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs can launch multiple "frames", which are displayed as individual windows in a graphical environment.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] On a text terminal, multiple frames are displayed stacked filling the entire terminal, and can be switched using the standard Emacs commands.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs can display or edit a variety of different types of text and adapts its behavior by entering add-on modes called "major modes".
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] There are major modes for many different purposes including editing ordinary text files, the source code of many markup and programming languages, as well as displaying web pages, directory listings and other system info.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Each major mode involves an Emacs Lisp program that extends the editor to behave more conveniently for the specified type of text.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The use of "minor modes" enables further customization.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] A GNU Emacs editing buffer can use only one major mode at a time, but multiple minor modes can operate simultaneously.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] These may operate directly on documents, as in the way the major mode for the C programming language defines a separate minor mode for each of its popular indent styles, or they may alter the editing environment.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Examples of the latter include a mode that adds the ability to undo changes to the window configuration and one that performs on-the-fly syntax checking.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] There is also a minor mode that allows multiple major modes to be used in a single file, for convenience when editing a document in which multiple programming languages are embedded.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs supports the capability to use it as an interpreter for the Emacs Lisp language without displaying the text editor user interface.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In batch mode, user configuration is not loaded and the terminal interrupt characters C-c and C-z will have their usual effect of exiting the program or suspending execution instead of invoking Emacs keybindings.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs has command line options to specify either a file to load and execute, or an Emacs Lisp function may be passed in from the command line.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs will start up, execute the passed-in file or function, print the results, then exit.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The shebang line `#!/usr/bin/emacs --script` allows the creation of standalone scripts in Emacs Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The *GNU Emacs Manual*, written by Richard Stallman, is bundled with GNU Emacs and can be viewed with the built-in info browser.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Two additional manuals, the *Emacs Lisp Reference Manual* by Bil Lewis, Richard Stallman, and Dan Laliberte and *An Introduction to Programming in Emacs Lisp* by Robert Chassell, are included.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] All three manuals are also published in book form by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs has support for many alphabets, scripts, writing systems, and cultural conventions and provides spell-checking for many languages by calling external programs such as ispell.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Version 24 added support for bidirectional text and left-to-right and right-to-left writing direction for languages such as Arabic, Persian and Hebrew.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Many character encoding systems, including UTF-8, are supported.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs uses UTF-8 for its encoding as of version 23, while prior versions used their own encoding internally and performed conversion upon load and save.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The internal encoding used by XEmacs is similar to that of GNU Emacs but differs in details.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The GNU Emacs user interface originated in English and, with the exception of the beginners' tutorial, has not been translated into any other language.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] A subsystem called *Emacspeak* enables visually impaired and blind users to control the editor through audio feedback.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The behavior of GNU Emacs can be modified and extended almost without limit by incorporating Emacs Lisp programs that define new commands, new buffer modes, new keymaps, add command-line options, and so on.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Many extensions providing user-facing functionality define a major mode (either for a new file type or to build a non-text-editing user interface); others define only commands or minor modes, or provide functions that enhance another extension.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Since version 24 GNU Emacs includes a built-in package manager accessible with the `list-packages` command that allows users to search for and install packages.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Historically, packages were downloaded manually, often distributed through the Usenet newsgroup gnu.emacs.sources.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Now, packages can be retrieved from various ELPA (Emacs Lisp Package Archive) repositories, including one run by the GNU Project.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Over time many popular packages have been included in Emacs by default; for example version 21 began bundling Org-mode, Calc, TRAMP, and many others.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In its early history, GNU Emacs often ran noticeably slower than rival text editors because the loading and interpreting of its Lisp-based code incurs a performance overhead.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Modern computers are powerful enough to run GNU Emacs with ease, but versions prior to 19.29 (released in 1995) couldn't edit files larger than 8 MB.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The file size limit was raised in successive versions, and 32 bit versions after GNU Emacs 23.2 can edit files up to 512 MB in size.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Emacs compiled on a 64-bit machine can handle much larger buffers.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] While GNU Emacs is largely written in Emacs Lisp, it makes extensive use of natively compiled C code to improve performance.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In addition to its own C code, it uses external libraries such as libxml2 for parsing XML.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Packages installed by the user can load dynamic modules.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Since version 28.1, Emacs can natively compile Emacs Lisp files via `libgccjit`, as opposed to just byte compiling them, resulting in a significant boost in performance.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs runs on a wide variety of operating systems, including DOS, Windows, and most Unix-like operating systems, such as Linux, the various BSDs, Solaris, AIX, HP-UX and macOS.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Many Unix-like systems include Emacs by default.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] In 2023 an official port for Android was released.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Version 23.1 removed support for some platforms deemed obsolete.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs runs both on text terminals and in graphical user interface (GUI) environments.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] On Unix-like operating systems, GNU Emacs can use the X Window System to produce its GUI either directly using Athena widgets or by using a "widget toolkit" such as Motif, LessTif, or GTK+.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs can also use the graphics systems native to macOS and Windows to provide menubars, toolbars, scrollbars and context menus conforming more closely to each platform's look and feel.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] The correct spelling is "GNU Emacs", not "GNU/Emacs", following the rules of English, in the construction "GNU Emacs" the word "GNU" modifies "Emacs." That is the right way to describe a program called Emacs which is a GNU package.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Lucid Emacs, based on an early version of GNU Emacs 19, was developed beginning in 1991 by Jamie Zawinski and others at Lucid Inc.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] One of the best-known forks in free software development occurred when the codebases of the two Emacs versions diverged and the separate development teams ceased efforts to merge them back into a single program.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] After Lucid filed for bankruptcy, Lucid Emacs was renamed XEmacs.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] XEmacs development has slowed, with the most recent stable version 21.4.22 released in January 2009, while GNU Emacs has implemented many formerly XEmacs-only features.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] This has led some users to proclaim XEmacs' obsolescence.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Changes in each Emacs release are listed in a NEWS file distributed with Emacs.
[src:emacs-editor/gnu-emacs] Changes brought about by *downgrading* to the previous release are listed in an "Antinews" file, often with some snarky commentary on why this might be desirable.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp does not support re-entrant continuations, but does support several ways of handling escape continuations.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Often, the same algorithm can be expressed in Lisp in either an imperative or a functional style.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] As noted above, Scheme tends to favor the functional style, using tail recursion and continuations to express control flow.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] However, imperative style is still quite possible.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] The style preferred by many Common Lisp programmers may seem more familiar to programmers used to structured languages such as C, while that preferred by Schemers more closely resembles pure-functional languages such as Haskell.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Because of Lisp's early heritage in list processing, it has a wide array of higher-order functions relating to iteration over sequences.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] In many cases where an explicit loop would be needed in other languages (like a `for` loop in C) in Lisp the same task can be accomplished with a higher-order function.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] A good example is a function which in Scheme is called `map` and in Common Lisp is called `mapcar`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] This applies the `+` function to each corresponding pair of list elements, yielding the result `(11 22 33 44 55)`.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Lisp syntax lends itself naturally to recursion.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Mathematical problems such as the enumeration of recursively defined sets are simple to express in this notation.
[src:emacs-editor/lisp-programming-language] Genera, renamed Open Genera, by Symbolics; Medley, written in Interlisp, originally a family of graphical operating systems that ran on Xerox's later Star workstations; Mezzano; Interim; ChrysaLisp, by developers of Tao Systems' TAOS; and also the Guix System for GNU/Linux.
